Abrami, who collects curious things, has cited a passage from Pliny (xxii. 24), who tells us that Pollio Romilius, who was then above a hundred years old. healthy and strong, was asked by Augustus how he had lived, and his answer was, “Intus mulso, foris oleo.’' He kept his inside meist with ‘ mulsum‚’ wine mixed with honey, and rubbed his skin with oil. Harduin (note on Pliny) says that Pollio followed the advice of Democritus, as we have it recorded by Diophanes (Geopon. xv. c. 7, and Athenaeus, ii. 46).
